<p class="mgSubItemTitleTxt">Minutes:</p>
<div class="mgWordPara"><div class="WordSection1">
<p style="font-weight: bold" class="MsoNormal">Presentation by the
Licensing Officer</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">The Sub-Committee was informed that this was
an application for a variation to the current premises licence
submitted by Stars Square Limited for the premises La Vuelta, 45
Tulse Hill, London, SW2 2TJ. The applicant sought permission to
vary the hours for the sale of alcohol and to add late night
refreshment for the following hours.</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<p style="font-weight: bold" class="MsoNormal">Sunday to
Thursday</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">12:00pm to 22:30pm</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<p style="font-weight: bold" class="MsoNormal">Friday and
Saturday</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">12:00pm to 00:30am</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<p style="font-weight: bold" class="MsoNormal">Friday and
Saturday</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">23:00pm to 00:00am</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<p style="font-weight: bold" class="MsoNormal">Sunday to
Thursday</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">07:30am to 23:00pm</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<p style="font-weight: bold" class="MsoNormal">Friday and
Saturday</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">07:30am to 01:00am</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">Ten representations were received in relation
to the application. These were submitted by the Licensing
Authority, Regulatory Services and the Commercial and Technical
Environmental Health Team (TEHT), together with eight local
residents. The representations related to the prevention of public
nuisance, the prevention of crime and disorder, and public safety.
Copies of the representations were provided to the applicant, and
the applicant had been invited to attend the hearing.</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">Licensing Officers had attempted to contact
the applicant by email on two occasions, namely on 15 January 2026
and 23 January 2026. In attendance on behalf of the responsible
authorities was Ms Marcia Green, together with Mr Matthew Onakoya
representing the Commercial and Technical Environmental Health
Team.</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">Two local residents were also in attendance,
Miss Camilla Walker, whose representation appeared on pages 57 to
61 of the report, and Mr Peter Learnat, whose representation
appeared on pages 71 to 73 of the report. The application form was
contained on pages 45 to 52 of the report. Representations in
opposition to the application were included on pages 53 to 80 of
the report, and a copy of the existing licence was contained on
pages 81 to 93 of the report.</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<p style="font-weight: bold" class="MsoNormal">Presentation by
Interested Parties</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">Marcia Green, representing the Licensing
Authority, said that:</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<ul style="margin-top:0cm">
<li class="MsoNormal" style="">The Licensing Authority submitted a
representation due to concerns that the variation, as applied for,
may undermined two licensing objectives, namely the prevention of
public nuisance and the prevention of crime and disorder. The
applicant sought to extend the hours for the sale of alcohol, add
late night refreshment on Fridays and Saturdays, and extend the
overall opening hours. These hours were significantly later than
those permitted under the existing licence.</li>
<li class="MsoNormal" style="">Under the Council&rsquo;s current
licensing policy, the premises was classed as a restaurant located
within a local shopping parade. For this type of premises in this
location, the recommended terminal hours were 23:00 hours from
Sunday to Thursday and midnight on Fridays and Saturdays. The hours
requested by the applicant exceeded these recommendations.</li>
<li class="MsoNormal" style="">The premises was situated within a
residential area, with homes located directly above, opposite, and
within the surrounding streets. This factor was considered
significant when assessing the potential for late-night
disturbance. Extending alcohol sales until 12:30 am and opening
hours until 1:00 am increased the likelihood of late-night noise
and disturbance affecting local residents, particularly those
residing above the premises.</li>
<li class="MsoNormal" style="">The Licensing Authority also raised
concerns regarding the potential for disorder associated with later
operating &nbsp;...&nbsp; <a href="mgAi.aspx?ID=67122" title=
"Link to view the full item text for item 4b, La Vuelta - (45 Tulse Hill, London SW2 2TJ) Variation">
view the full minutes text for item 4b</a></li>
</ul>
</div>
</div> 
					
