<div class="mgWordPara"><div class="WordSection1">
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<p style="font-weight: bold" class="MsoNormal">Presentation by the
Licensing Officer</p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><a name="x__Hlk222144046" id=
"x__Hlk222144046">&nbsp;</a></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="">The Sub-Committee was informed
that this was an application for a review of the current premises
licence brought forward by the Metropolitan Police, following a
number of incidents that had occurred at the premises. In
attendance for the Metropolitan Police was PC David Watson and on
behalf of the applicant was Mr David Dadd&rsquo;s. One
representation was submitted by the Licensing Authority supporting
the polices review of the premises.</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="">&nbsp;</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="">The application form from the
police could be found on pages 104 to 105 of the report. The
Licensing Authority representation could be found on pages 107 to
108 of the report. The petition support of the premises was on
pages 109 to 110 of the report, and a copy of the premises licence
was on pages 111 to 121.</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<p style="font-weight: bold" class="MsoNormal">Presentation by the
Applicant</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">Mr. David Dadd`s, Legal representative for
Aquarium Tapas Bar, informed the Sub-Committee that:</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<ul style="margin-top:0cm">
<li class="MsoNormal" style="">Mr Dadd firstly thanked the
Metropolitan Police Service and colleagues for meeting with him on
several occasions during the review period. He also expressed his
thanks to Democratic Services and the Licensing Officers for their
work throughout this time.</li>
<li class="MsoNormal" style="">He stated that the review had
centred on a single isolated incident in March 2025, which had not
repeated itself. He acknowledged that the licensing objectives had
been undermined; however, those matters had been addressed. He
confirmed that they had been addressed through conditions, with the
Police acting as the principal source of advice on crime and
disorder, and that the Police had been satisfied that the proposed
steps would promote the licensing objectives.</li>
<li class="MsoNormal" style="">Mr Dadd`s noted that the licence had
originally contained 15 conditions. He stated that the revised
conditions submitted to the Committee and the Licensing Authority
would, in effect, supersede the existing conditions in order to
tidy up the licence. He confirmed that, following discussions
between himself, the Police, and the Licensing Authority, condition
number 8 had been removed, resulting in 14 conditions.</li>
<li class="MsoNormal" style="">He further stated that it had been
agreed that these conditions would replace the previous conditions
in their entirety and that the exercise had been intended to
rationalise the licence.</li>
</ul>
<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin-left:36.0pt">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">In response to questions from Members, the Mr
Dadd`s confirmed:</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">&nbsp;</p>
<ul style="margin-top:0cm">
<li class="MsoNormal" style="">Mr Dadd stated that, during several
meetings with the Police and the licensee, it had been established
that the Police lacked confidence in the existing DPS. He stated
that both he and the Police had held concerns regarding the DPS and
whether he had exercised sufficient control over patrons.</li>
<li class="MsoNormal" style="">However, he confirmed that the
licensee had since addressed those concerns through the appointment
of a new DPS. He further stated that the proposed DPS held a
personal licence, which had addressed all concerns going
forward.</li>
<li class="MsoNormal" style="">Mr Dadd also noted that matters
arising at the premises had been very rare and stated that, with
the change of DPS and adherence to closing times, the premises had
benefited from significant support from local residents. He further
stated that the premises had been considered unique and bespoke
